  "method": "We propose Streaming Query-Conditioned Compressive Memory (SQCM), a modular architecture that separates short-range computation from long-range recall. A lightweight dual-branch encoder processes the incoming stream (text tokens, video frames, or state-action tuples) with cheap local modeling and a tightly windowed global self-attention, while a long-term memory bank is built online as a sparse, query-addressable store. Each stream segment (e.g., 512–1k text tokens, a short video clip, or N steps of an episode) is summarized into a small set of multi-view keys and a tiny cache of core tokens; future steps retrieve only from this bank instead of attending over the full past, keeping compute sub-quadratic and near-constant with stream length.\n\nFor ingestion, each segment produces k multi-view keys by inserting special viewer tokens that learn to capture diverse semantics of the same content. In parallel, we compute token-level importance within the segment using attention/gradient attribution and select a few core tokens along with their positional indices. The memory thus stores a two-tier entry per segment: (1) multi-view keys for fast approximate addressing and (2) a compact value set of core tokens that preserves structure and can be re-inserted into attention when needed. For videos, we maintain a small FIFO of recent segment features and apply motion/ego-compensation to align them before summarization; for text/episodes we retain absolute or section-relative positions to enable structural alignment.\n\nAt inference time, the current model state (decoder state, task head, or explicit query vector) soft-matches against the memory’s viewer keys using a max-pooled similarity over views, retrieving the top-M relevant segments. Only the union of these segments’ core tokens (e.g., 2–4 segments × 16–64 tokens each) is brought into the context via cross-attention, gated by a learned relevance score so that the model pays for long-range computation only when evidence is likely downstream. For streaming video, recalled features are optionally warped into the current frame’s reference before cross-attention to reduce noise; for text, recalled tokens re-use their stored positional indices to preserve syntax/section cues. The local branch handles most computation, while the global branch is reserved for the small recalled set, keeping total attention cost bounded.\n\nMemory maintenance combines consolidation, deduplication, and eviction. We update existing memory entries with an uncertainty-weighted exponential moving average so novel or ambiguous content is written more strongly, while routine content produces smaller updates. To prevent bloat, we filter redundancies by semantic similarity with a recency-aware policy and evict via a relevance–age score. The selector and gates are trained end-to-end with auxiliary supervision that encourages retrieved memory to overlap with gold evidence when available; hard retrieval is approximated with differentiable top-k or Gumbel sampling during training and replaced by ANN search over viewer keys at serving time.\n\nAcross modalities, SQCM drops the need for full O(T^2) attention over long contexts: processing is O(T) for local compute, plus O(log B) for ANN over a bounded memory B and O(M·K) attention on recalled tokens (M segments, K tokens each). Typical settings (e.g., k=8 viewer keys per segment, M≤4, K≤64) provide robust recall of distant evidence while preserving a small, predictable compute budget.",
  "rationale": "Long-context models struggle because they (a) pay quadratic cost for indiscriminate attention and (b) diffuse attention mass over many irrelevant tokens, causing forgetting of distant but crucial evidence. SQCM attacks both by compressing history into query-addressable, multi-view keys and a tiny set of core tokens, and by retrieving only what the current state deems relevant. Multi-view keys preserve diverse semantics so a single segment can be recalled for many future questions without dense late interaction, while core tokens plus positional indices retain the fine-grained structure needed to reason once retrieved.\n\nStreaming design and alignment maintain fidelity over time: in video, warping reduces temporal drift; in text/episodes, stored indices anchor recalled tokens to their original structure. Uncertainty-weighted consolidation prevents catastrophic overwriting while redundancy filtering keeps memory lean. The dual-branch encoder further reduces compute by reserving expensive global attention for a handful of recalled tokens, letting a cheap local pathway handle most steps. Together, these choices yield effective, scalable memory of distant information under tight compute budgets.",
