  "method": "We propose a dual‑scale streaming transformer with a sparse Evidence Capsule Memory (ECM) that keeps long‑range information available at constant compute. The model processes inputs in short causal chunks with standard local attention, while long‑range information is represented by a compact set of capsules (B≈32–128) and a global attribute vector. Each capsule stores a key (embedding), a lightweight payload (short textual/event summary or compressed KV), and metadata (time, uncertainty, TTL). The model only cross‑attends to the top‑M capsules (e.g., M=8) that are dynamically retrieved per chunk; all other long tokens are summarized into capsules offline from the main attention path, so end‑to‑end complexity grows roughly linearly with sequence length (windowed attention + sparse cross‑attention), not quadratically.\n\nCapsule formation is event‑centric and modality‑aware. For videos, a tiny frame‑selector produces 2–3 core frames per segment and a lightweight captioner generates progress‑aware per‑frame captions; adjacent captions are compared to detect event boundaries, and only frames around boundaries are passed to the heavy LVLM while the rest are summarized into capsules. For long documents, a small sidecar head performs boundary detection (section shifts, entity/state changes) and emits succinct progress‑style summaries that become capsule payloads. Each candidate capsule receives an embedding from the backbone; novelty and salience are computed with respect to existing memory and the current query state.\n\nMemory is kept compact, diverse, and up‑to‑date via prototype‑guided consolidation and efficient re‑ranking. A discriminative prototype layer clusters candidate and resident capsules by cosine similarity, enforcing distinction so capsules cover different topics/events and providing a confidence score to prioritize ambiguous yet important content. When the memory is full, we maintain a top‑K replacement shortlist and apply lightweight adjacent‑swap pairwise comparisons to refine which capsules to admit/evict using a scorer that balances relevance (to current/anticipated queries), novelty (diversity vs existing capsules), and stability (confidence/TTL). In parallel, a global attribute vector is updated each chunk by attending over the current capsules conditioned on the last token/hidden state; this attribute is injected back into token updates (e.g., as a special token or conditioning gate) so the backbone always carries a compact summary of distant context.\n\nAt inference, each chunk runs: (1) local windowed attention; (2) retrieval of top‑M capsules by fast similarity search over capsule keys followed by the efficient pairwise RTL refinement; (3) one or two layers of cross‑attention from tokens to those M capsules; and (4) a global‑attribute update that is fed back into all layers via residual conditioning. For videos, only selector‑chosen core frames are fed to the LVLM; non‑selected frames contribute via their capsules. For text or mixed episodes, only boundary‑level summaries persist; raw distant tokens are discarded. This preserves access to far‑past evidence with bounded compute while mitigating forgetting through both the persistent capsules and the continually refreshed global attribute.\n\nTraining proceeds in two stages. First, pretrain the capsule extractor and selector with self‑supervised signals (next‑sentence/temporal order, masked span prediction) and weak supervision for evidence localization (e.g., supervision from QA rationales or distillation from short‑context full‑attention runs) so capsules capture answer‑bearing facts and event transitions. Second, jointly fine‑tune the re‑ranking scorer and cross‑attention using task losses, with budgeted memory curricula (vary B and M) to make retrieval robust. An aging/TTL objective and prototype separation loss stabilize the memory over long horizons. The entire pipeline remains causal and streaming, enabling deployment on very long documents, episodes, and videos without exhausting compute.",
  "rationale": "The method replaces costly global attention with a compact, query‑adaptive memory that summarizes distant content into a small set of event‑centric capsules. Local computation remains dense only within a sliding window, while long‑range access is achieved through sparse cross‑attention to M≪N capsules, keeping complexity near‑linear in sequence length. Progress‑aware boundary detection and lightweight frame selection ensure capsules capture the right moments, preventing drift and redundancy.\n\nForgetting is alleviated in two ways: (1) a persistent set of discriminative, prototype‑diverse capsules maintains stable representations of distinct long‑range facts/events, and (2) a global attribute vector—updated by attending over capsules and injected into token updates—carries a compact, always‑present summary that conditions the model even when no capsules are explicitly retrieved. Efficient adjacent‑swap re‑ranking lets the system maintain and refresh memory under strict budgets with minimal overhead, so distant information remains findable and usable without quadratic cost.",
